üìä Detailed Explanation

What Was Wrong:

Your original code was making 4 API calls per row:

getRange().getValue() - Read cell 1

getRange().getValue() - Read cell 2

getRange().setValue() - Write cell 3

getRange().setValue() - Write cell 4

For 1000 rows: 4,000 API calls √ó ~100ms each = 400+ seconds (6+ minutes)

Plus each API call has overhead for:

Network latency

Authentication

Data serialization

Rate limiting

How the Fix Works:

The optimized version makes only 2 API calls total:

getRange().getValues() - Read ALL rows at once

getRange().setValues() - Write ALL results at once

For 1000 rows: 2 API calls √ó ~100ms = ~200ms base time + processing

Processing happens in memory:

// Read once

var data = sheet.getRange(2, 1, 1000, 2).getValues();¬†// 1 call

// Process in JavaScript (fast - no API calls)

var results = data.map(function(row) {

¬†¬†// Pure computation - happens instantly

¬†¬†return [row[1] * 2 + 10, row[1] > 50 ? 'High' : 'Low'];

});

// Write once

sheet.getRange(2, 3, 1000, 2).setValues(results);¬†// 1 call

Why This Approach:

Batch Operations: Minimize API calls by reading/writing in bulk

Memory Processing: JavaScript operations are 1000x faster than API calls

Chunking: For very large datasets, process in manageable pieces

Rate Limit Friendly: Fewer calls = less likely to hit quotas

